# Coding Standards and Best Practices

## TypeScript Guidelines

### Type Safety
- Always use strict TypeScript configuration
- Prefer explicit types over `any`
- Use type inference when types are obvious
- Define interfaces for complex data structures
- Use utility types like `Partial<T>`, `Pick<T>`, `Omit<T>` when appropriate

### Naming Conventions
- Use PascalCase for components, interfaces, and types
- Use camelCase for variables, functions, and properties
- Use UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for constants
- Use pascalCase for file names (except for api routes which use kebab-case)

### File Organization
- One component per file
- Export components as default exports
- Use named exports for utilities and types
- Group related files in directories

## React Guidelines

### Component Structure
```typescript
// Type definitions
interface ComponentProps {
  // Define props here
}

// Component definition
export function ComponentName({ prop1, prop2 }: ComponentProps) {
  // Component logic here

  return (
    // JSX here
  );
}
```

### Hooks Usage
- Use custom hooks for reusable logic
- Follow the rules of hooks (only call at top level)
- Use `useCallback` for functions passed as props
- Use `useMemo` for expensive calculations
- Use `useEffect` for side effects

### State Management
- Use React Query for server state
- Use local state for UI state
- Prefer composition over prop drilling
- Use context sparingly and only for truly global state

## Styling Guidelines

### Tailwind CSS
- Use Tailwind utility classes for styling
- Create custom components for repeated patterns
- Use CSS variables for theme values
- Follow mobile-first responsive design
- Use semantic class names when possible

### Component Styling
```typescript
// Good: Using Tailwind classes
<div className="flex items-center justify-between p-4 bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm">
  <h2 className="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Title</h2>
</div>

// Less good: Using CSS modules for complex styles
import styles from './Component.module.css';
<div className={styles.container}>
```

## Error Handling

### Try-Catch Patterns
```typescript
try {
  const result = await someAsyncOperation();
  return result;
} catch (error) {
  console.error('Operation failed:', error);
  throw new Error('User-friendly error message');
}
```

### Effect TS
Effect TS library is used in backend code (only), the Errors thrown by the backend code is prefered to be a custom Effect Error when possible, only in very rare cases vanilla Error should be used.

The errors could have custom logic such as inheriting the Stack Trace from the cause instead of creating a new one.

```typescript
class ExampleError extends Data.TaggedError('ExampleError')<{
  readonly message: string;
  readonly cause?: unknown;
  readonly otherProp: boolean;
}> {}

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  Effect.fail(new ExampleError({message: "The reason", cause: ErrorCause, otherProp: true}))
});

### Error Boundaries
- Implement error boundaries for component error handling
- Provide fallback UI for error states
- Log errors appropriately

## Performance Guidelines

### Code Splitting
- Use dynamic imports for route-based code splitting
- Lazy load components that are not immediately needed
- Use `React.lazy()` for component lazy loading

### Optimization
- Use `React.memo()` for expensive components
- Implement proper key props for lists
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders
- Use `useCallback` and `useMemo` appropriately

## Testing Guidelines

### Component Testing
- Write tests for complex business logic
- Test user interactions and edge cases
- Use meaningful test descriptions
- Mock external dependencies

### Test Structure
```typescript
describe('ComponentName', () => {
  it('should render correctly', () => {
    // Test implementation
  });

  it('should handle user interactions', () => {
    // Test implementation
  });
});
```

## Code Quality

### ESLint and Prettier
- Follow ESLint rules strictly
- Use Prettier for consistent formatting
- Run `pnpm check` before committing
- Fix all linting errors and warnings

### Comments and Documentation
- Write clear, concise comments for complex logic
- Document public APIs and interfaces
- Use JSDoc for function documentation
- Keep comments up to date with code changes

### Git Practices
- Write descriptive commit messages
- Use conventional commit format
- Keep commits focused and atomic
- Review code before merging
